What is the structure of your dataset?¶

Now, there are rows of flight data in the dataset with 29 features originally.
Variable descriptions Name Description 1 Month 1-12
2 DayofMonth 1-31
3 DayOfWeek 1 (Monday) - 7 (Sunday)
4 DepTime actual departure time (local, hhmm)
5 CRSDepTime scheduled departure time (local, hhmm)
6 ArrTime actual arrival time (local, hhmm)
7 CRSArrTime scheduled arrival time (local, hhmm)
8 UniqueCarrier unique carrier code
9 FlightNum flight number
10 TailNum plane tail number
11 ActualElapsedTime (actual) in minutes
12 CRSElapsedTime (scheduled) in minutes
13 AirTime in minutes 14 ArrDelay (Difference in minutes between scheduled and actual arrival time)
15 DepDelay (Difference in minutes between scheduled and actual departure time. )
16 Origin origin IATA airport code
17 Dest destination IATA airport code
(Code assigned by IATA and commonly used to identify a carrier. As the same code may have been assigned to different carriers over time, the code is not always unique.) 18 Distance in miles 19 TaxiIn taxi in time, in minutes
20 TaxiOut taxi out time, in minutes
21 CarrierDelay in minutes
22 WeatherDelay in minutes
23 NASDelay (National Air System Delay) in minutes
24 SecurityDelay in minutes
25 LateAircraftDelay in minutes

A reference for delay definitions: here

  • Carrier Delay
    Carrier delay is within the control of the air carrier. Examples of occurrences that may determine carrier delay are: aircraft cleaning, aircraft damage, awaiting the arrival of connecting passengers or crew, baggage, bird strike, cargo loading, catering, computer, outage-carrier equipment, crew legality (pilot or attendant rest), damage by hazardous goods, engineering inspection, fueling, handling disabled passengers, late crew, lavatory servicing, maintenance, oversales, potable water servicing, removal of unruly passenger, slow boarding or seating, stowing carry-on baggage, weight and balance delays.
  • Late Arrival Delay
    Arrival delay at an airport due to the late arrival of the same aircraft at a previous airport. The ripple effect of an earlier delay at downstream airports is referred to as delay propagation.
  • NAS Delay
    Delay that is within the control of the National Airspace System (NAS) may include: non-extreme weather conditions, airport operations, heavy traffic volume, air traffic control, etc. Delays that occur after Actual Gate Out are usually attributed to the NAS and are also reported through OPSNET.
  • Security Delay
    Security delay is caused by evacuation of a terminal or concourse, re-boarding of aircraft because of security breach, inoperative screening equipment and/or long lines in excess of 29 minutes at screening areas.
  • Weather Delay
    Weather delay is caused by extreme or hazardous weather conditions that are forecasted or manifest themselves on point of departure, enroute, or on point of arrival.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

  • What causes the longer delays?

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

  • 2 factors of delay (departure delay + elapsed time extension)
    • arrival delay = ArrDelay = ArrTime - CRSArrTime
    • departure delay = DepDelay = DepTime - CRSDepTime
    • elapsed time extension = ActualElapsedTime - CRSElapsedTime
  • Distance
  • 5 delay factors given in the dataset
    • WeatherDelay, NAS Delay, SecurityDelay, LateAircraftDelay

The delayed arrivals are more interesting as they can be caused i) on land, i.e. delayed departure; and ii) in air, i.e. weather conditions which make planes take extra time before landing or change landing airports. This will be analyzed by examining 2 variables: DepDelay and delay_elapesd. The distribution is right-skewed with the mean around 0.

Analyzing the delay factor together¶

In [121]:
# Identifying which type of delay causes most of the arrival delays: 
p_car = flights[(~flights.CarrierDelay.isnull()) & (flights.CarrierDelay!=0)].shape[0]/flights.shape[0]
p_wea = flights[(~flights.WeatherDelay.isnull()) & (flights.WeatherDelay!=0)].shape[0]/flights.shape[0]
p_nas = flights[(~flights.NASDelay.isnull()) & (flights.NASDelay!=0)].shape[0]/flights.shape[0]
p_sec = flights[(~flights.SecurityDelay.isnull()) & (flights.SecurityDelay!=0)].shape[0]/flights.shape[0]
p_late = flights[(~flights.LateAircraftDelay.isnull()) & (flights.LateAircraftDelay!=0)].shape[0]/flights.shape[0]

delay_types = pd.Series([p_car,p_wea,p_nas,p_sec,p_late], index=["car","wea","nas","sec","late"]).sort_values(ascending=False)
sb.barplot(delay_types.index, delay_types, color=sb.color_palette()[0]);
  • National Airspace System (NAS) related delays are the most frequent. This is not surprising as this is probably broadest category which includes delays related to the information systems, cargo services, rules, regulations, policies, procedures, personnel and equipment.

Note:

  • more than one delay can cause an arrival delay
  • the unspecified types of delays could be dumped into a NAS category, boosting up its portion
In [124]:
# Let's look at the distribution of on how many minutes each delay factor can prolong the flight time
# First, create dummy dataframes with 2 columns, delay type and time
dummy = pd.DataFrame()
delay_types = ["NASDelay","LateAircraftDelay","CarrierDelay","WeatherDelay","SecurityDelay"]

for type in delay_types:
    dum = pd.DataFrame()
    dum["time"] = flights[(flights[type] != 0) & (~flights[type].isnull())][type]
    dum["type"] = type
    dummy = dummy.append(dum)

plt.figure(figsize=[15,6])
plt.subplot(1,2,1)
sb.violinplot(data= dummy, x="type", y="time")
plt.xticks(rotation=30);
plt.subplot(1,2,2)
sb.violinplot(data= dummy, x="type", y="time")
plt.ylim([-50,150])
plt.xticks(rotation=30);

The figures suggest that CarrierDelay is related with longer delays, followed by NASDelay, LateAirCraftDelay and WeatherDelay. As SecurityDelay has comparatively less impact, in terms of length and frequency of the delays, it can be removed from further analysis.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

As discussed earlier, I concentrated in 4 (independent) variables which can influence the arrival delay (= dependent variable): distance of the flights, time in the air, elapsed time, departure delay. Distribution of the ArrDelay is right-skewed with the mean about 0, which is resonable expectation, as very few flights arrive earlier than scheduled time. ArrDelay is attributed to 2 direct causes -- Departure delay and Elapsed time delay, which were further analyzed.

Distribution of the Departure delay is right-skewed with the mean about 0, which is more similar to the distribution of Arrival delay.
Distribution of the Elapsed time delay is more symmetric with the mean about 0. Also, the variance of the Elapsed time delay is smaller than the variances of the former two.

To analyze the distributions and draw inferences:

  • some outliers were removed from the data set
  • the histograms were visualized using the log-scale
  • the other delay types/factors' distributions were analysed using visual plots
  • these plots suggest that larger portion of the delays are NAS related delays, which is, as discussed, could be a reasonable expectation
  • the least relevant type/factor of the delay, to which smaller share of delays is attributed, will be dropped from the dataframe

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

  • The outliers were looked for by analyzing the extreme values, first, on the distribution plots, then, close-up tables
  • It was found that the extreme distances are related to the flights from/to Hawaii
  • There were 3 significant "negative" delays in elapsed time which caused arrival delays, which does not make sense. Moreover, the actual time in the air for these flights were shorter than scheduled times. I assumed that these are related to emergency landing, and removed them as outliers.

  • The strong correlation between DepDelay and ArrDelay was discussed above.
  • delay_elapsed, as can be seen in the plot, has very little effect on ArrDelay, hypothetically, becasue delays caused in air are very little compared to other factors.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

  • It was found that the Distance does not have a big effect on DepDelay.
  • It was also found that the flights with delay_elapsed between 200 and 400 minutes are more likely to have longer NASdelay time.
  • As for delay_elapsed, the longer the DepDelay is, the longer CarrierDelay and WeatherDelay are likely to be.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

  • Given the definition of NASDelay above, it's interesting to observe that longer deley_elapsed is associated with with longer NASDelay. This might be due to system, procedures and regulations due to which a plane is not able to depart on time.

  • Regarding CarrierDelay and WeatherDelay, they are less likely to occur, however they are stronger associated with longer DepDelay.
